2. Modeling¶

(1) First model¶

Conv2D -> Conv2D -> MaxPool2D -> Conv2D -> Conv2D -> MaxPool2D -> Flatten -> Dense -> Dense -> output¶

The activation function of hidden layer except for the output layer is "relu", and that of output layer is "sigmoid."¶

Any stride is not applied, because the images seem homogeneous.¶

In [9]:
model = Sequential()

model.add(Conv2D(filters=16, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(Conv2D(filters=16, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

model.add(Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(units=256, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(units=1, activation='sigmoid'))

batch_size = 256

model.build(input_shape=(batch_size, 64, 64, 3))

model.summary()

    dataframe = image_train,
    x_col='id', # filenames

(2) 2nd model -- Batch normalization¶

At the 2nd model, batch normalization is tried: Based on the first model, 4 batch normalization layers are inserted between convolution layers / convolution layer and max pooling layer.¶

In [15]:
model_bn = Sequential()

model_bn.add(Conv2D(filters=16, kernel_size=(3,3)))
model_bn.add(BatchNormalization())
model_bn.add(Activation('relu'))
model_bn.add(Conv2D(filters=16, kernel_size=(3,3)))
model_bn.add(BatchNormalization())
model_bn.add(Activation('relu'))
model_bn.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

model_bn.add(Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3,3)))
model_bn.add(BatchNormalization())
model_bn.add(Activation('relu'))
model_bn.add(Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3,3)))
model_bn.add(BatchNormalization())
model_bn.add(Activation('relu'))
model_bn.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2)))

model_bn.add(Flatten())
model_bn.add(Dense(units=256, activation='relu'))
model_bn.add(Dense(units=1, activation='sigmoid'))

model_bn.build(input_shape=(batch_size, 64, 64, 3))

model_bn.summary()

3. Discussion¶

Normal CNN model, CNN model including Batch normalization, VGGNet model and ResNet model are tried for detecting cancer. Considering accuracy, CNN model with Batch normalization is the best. (accuracy: 0.9058, validation accuracy: 0.8789)¶

Also this model decreases loss further. But there is some inconsistency between accuracy and validation accuracy, compared with 1st model (CNN without batch normalization). I do not have any idea about this background: in comparison with 2 model (1st & 2nd), the basic structure of layer is the same; 4 batch normalization layers are added to the 1st model. I guess that batch normalization layers might give rise to inconsistency.¶

At VGGNet and ResNet, 2 things are found: 1) loss is relatively high, 2) validation accuracy is constantly higher than accuracy.¶

4. Conclusion¶

At this mini project for detecting cancer, 4 models are tried. At the end, CNN model with batch normalization would be the best. (accuracy: 0.9058, validation accuracy: 0.8789) The effect of batch normalization would be confirmed.¶

For test set, which is submitted to Kaggle site, score is 0.759.¶
